'''The Gender Trust''' is a [[United Kingdom]] charitable organization promoting public education about [[transgender]] and [[gender identity]] issues and providing information to those affected. It is based in [[Horsham]] and [[Henfield]], [[West Sussex]]. Gender Trust spokesmen comment on occasion to the news about [[transexualism]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Abbott|first=Stephen|title=Charity blasts PCT for proposed sex change cuts|url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/thechiswick/chiswicknews/1104160.charity_blasts_pct_for_proposed_sex_change_cuts/|quote=But the Gender Trust said the move "would put medicine back 30 years in its understanding of what transsexualism is.|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=Richmond and Twickenham Times|date=January 10, 2007}}</ref> For example, when the 2004 [[Big Brother (TV series)|Big Brother]] winner was a transsexual, a GenderTrust spokesman said of the program: "It's raised the general public's awareness that transsxuals are just ordinary people."<ref name=nadia>{{cite news|last=Bradbury|first=Jennifer|title=Important to gain acceptance|quote=A spokesman for the Gender Trust, a UK charity which offers advice, education, information and support on gender identity issues to transsexuals and professional people who come across transsexuals in the course of their work, said of Nadia's success on BB: "We feel it has been a positive experience. It's raised the general public's awareness that transsexuals are just ordinary people."|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/tm_objectid=14520460&method=full&siteid=50081&headline=so-important-to-gain-acceptance-name_page.html|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=Evening Chronicle|date=August 11, 2004}}</ref>  It has criticised employers for rarely thinking about the need for sex change or of the difficulty of sex change operations on their employees.<ref>{{cite news|last=Radnedge|first=Aidan|title=Child who wants sex change goes back to school as girl|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/875249-child-who-wants-sex-change-goes-back-to-school-as-girl|quote="Michelle Bridgman, a psychotherapist and project manager for the Gender Trust charity, described the child’s bullies as ‘barbaric’.|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=Metro|date=September 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bourke|first=Amy|title=Employers challenged over trans policies|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2007/04/04/employers-challenged-over-trans-policies/|quote=Not long before the Gender Equality duty (GED) comes into force, the Gender Trust has said that employers are often surprised what a turbulent process changing gender can be.|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=Pink News|date=April 4, 2007}}</ref>  And it has supported [[Lady Gaga]], stating in the ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]'': "Lady GaGa does so much good work for the trans­gender and gay community."<ref>[http://www.dailystar.co.uk/playlist/view/198541/Eminem-s-Lady-GaGa-row/ Eminem's Lady Gaga row]  ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]'', 30th June 2011</ref>

In 1997, The Gender Trust was one of the 65 groups awarded money grants by the [[National Lottery Charities Board]].<ref name=moneygrants>{{cite news|title=Transsexuals win extra change from the lottery|quote=A charity for transsexuals is among 65 recipients of lottery money grants announced today by the National Lottery Charities Board. The Gender Trust, of Horsham and Henfield, West Sussex, is awarded pounds 33,700 in grants to health, disability and care projects totalling pounds 9.6m.|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/transsexuals-win-extra-change-from-the-lottery-1283090.html|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=The Independent|date=January 14, 1997}}</ref> In 2003, The Gender Trust was one of the many UK support groups suggested for [[intersex]] persons and people with gender identity problems.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ford|first=Coreena|title=Stuck in the middle|quote=There are many support groups in the UK for intersex people and those with gender-identity problems, including . . . Cross + Roads Gender Identity Support and Transwatch UK: 01388-607925 or e-mail paula@crossroads-gid-support.org.uk or andrea@crossroads-gid-support.org.uk The Gender Trust: 07000-790347. ATR-X Support Group: 01606-44943. Mermaids (family support group for children and teenagers with gender-identity issues): 07020-935066.|url=http://www.sundaysun.co.uk/lifestyle-news/health-news/2003/01/12/stuck-in-the-middle-79310-12525618/|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=Sunday Sun|date=January 12, 2003}}</ref> In 2007, an advice panel suggested Gender Trust as one of several professional organizations from which a person troubled with gender identity issues can seek guidance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ask The Panel for advice|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=209289&sectioncode=26|quote=They can also seek guidance from professional organisations such as Press for Change, The Gender Trust (www.gendertrust.org.uk) or TheGender Identity and Research Education Society (www.gires.org.uk).|publisher=Times Higher Education|accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref> 

